e}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/39023"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 6-year-old boy is brought by his mother to see the general practitioner. She is worried that he is constantly eating. His hunger is insatiable to the extent she has to lock food away to keep him from eating it. His mother is also concerned that he is having more frequent temper tantrums than his peers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe was delivered at term via spontaneous vaginal delivery with an unremarkable obstetric history. Initially, she reports he was \u0022kind of floppy\u0022 as an infant, but this resolved by 10 months. In terms of his developmental history, he started sitting without support at the age of 1 year, crawling at 1.5 years and walking at 2.5 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination he has almond shaped eyes, thin lips and a narrow nasal bridge. He has small hands and a scoliosis. His weight is 30 kg, his height 90 cm and his BMI 37.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prader Willi syndrome","Angelman syndrome","Hypothyroidism","Bardet-Biedl syndrome","Di George syndrome"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child has the \u003Cstrong\u003EPrader-Willi syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E. This is the consequence of a genetic disorder caused by lack of expression of genes on paternal chromosome 15.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EClassical clinical features include hypotonia, hypoglycaemia, feeding difficulties and a weak cry at birth. Global developmental delay and undescended testes are common. By the age of 5, excessive hunger and subsequent morbid obesity is typical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBardet-Biedl syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is an autosomal recessive disorder caused by the biallelic loss of function in at least 26 genes. It is a disorder that shares some similarities with Prader-Willi syndrome, including obesity and intellectual disability. However, Bardet-Biedl syndrome also involves other features which not present in this case, including retinal degeneration, polydactyly and renal abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAngelman syndrome \u003C/strong\u003Eis a genetic disorder caused by lack of expression of genes on maternal chromosome 15. Typically, a child with Angelman syndrome has intellectual disability and seizures. They have a happy demeanor with frequent laughter. Angelman syndrome is a less likely diagnosis in this case as it does not explain this patient\u0027s hyperphagia or temper tantrums.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypothyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E is an unlikely explanation for this child\u0027s problems. Lethargy and hypotonia may be seen in hypothyroidism and weight gain may occur, but it is not associated with insatiable hunger. Coarse facial features, thick tongue, hoarse cry are also seen in hypothyroidism, but this child did not have these facial features. Affected infants are likely to have already suffered irreversible brain damage before signs of the condition begin to appear.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDi George syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E would not fit the diagnosis for this case. This syndrome is characterised by feeding difficulties, failure to gain weight and various gastrointestinal problems. Different facial features, such as an underdeveloped chin, low-set ears, wide-set eyes, cleft palate or a narrow groove in the upper lip are seen in Di George syndrome (22q11.2 deletion syndrome)\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The Prader Willi syndrome is characterised by an uncontrolled desire to be constantly eating."],"references":["Maranga C, Fernandes TG, Bekman E, da Rocha ST. Angelman syndrome: a journey through the brain. FEBS J. 2020 Jun;287(11):2154-2175. doi: 10.1111/febs.15258. Epub 2020 Mar 14. PMID: 32087041.","Butler MG, Miller JL, Forster JL. Prader-Willi Syndrome - Clinical Genetics, Diagnosis and Treatment Approaches: An Update. Curr Pediatr Rev. 2019;15(4):207-244. doi: 10.2174/1573396315666190716120925. PMID: 31333129; PMCID: PMC7040524.","Cassidy SB, Schwartz S, Miller JL, Driscoll DJ. Prader-Willi syndrome. Genet Med. 2012 Jan;14(1):10-26. doi: 10.1038/gim.0b013e31822bead0. Epub 2011 Sep 26. PMID: 22237428."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23352"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12549"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/23352"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-08-21T17:56:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2023-08-21T17:56:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5048"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39023"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"42","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/42"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddec","name":"Genetics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49